  "footnotes": [
    "Periplus of the Erythraean Sea (c. 1st c. CE): A Greek merchant manual describing the East African coast ('Azania') and its trade in ivory, tortoise shell, and coconut oil; the earliest written evidence of Indian Ocean commerce along the Swahili Coast.",
    "Shirazi tradition: Many Swahili city-states claimed descent from Persian settlers from Shiraz; modern scholarship sees this as a legitimising myth constructed in the Islamic period, not literal migration, though Persian commercial contact was real.",
    "Kilwa Sultanate (c. 957–1513): The most powerful of the Swahili city-states; controlled the gold trade from Great Zimbabwe via Sofala; its Great Mosque (c. 1300) and Husuni Kubwa palace are among the finest medieval structures in sub-Saharan Africa; Ibn Battuta called Kilwa 'one of the most beautiful cities in the world' (1331).",
    "Vasco da Gama (1498): Portuguese arrival shattered the existing Indian Ocean trade network; Mombasa resisted and was attacked twice; Malindi allied with Portugal; the Estado da India imposed a system of cartaz (trading licences) to extract revenue.",
    "Fort Jesus, Mombasa (1593): Built by the Portuguese to anchor their East African trade route; changed hands nine times; the 1696–1698 Omani siege (33 months) ended Portuguese dominance; now a UNESCO World Heritage Site.",
    "Seyyid Said (r. 1806–1856): Sultan of Oman who moved his capital to Zanzibar in 1840 to control the lucrative slave and clove trades; at its peak Zanzibar exported 40,000–50,000 enslaved people per year; his death triggered the 1856 split between Oman and Zanzibar.",
    "Heligoland–Zanzibar Treaty (1890): Britain and Germany divided East African spheres of influence; Germany ceded Heligoland (North Sea island) to Britain in exchange for Zanzibar; established the boundaries of British East Africa and German East Africa.",
    "Zanzibar Revolution (12 January 1964): The Arab-dominated sultanate was overthrown by the Afro-Shirazi Party; several thousand Arabs and Indians were killed; within months Zanzibar merged with Tanganyika to form the United Republic of Tanzania, though it retains semi-autonomous status.",
    "Maji Maji Rebellion (1905–1907): Widespread uprising against German colonial rule in Tanganyika; 200,000–300,000 Africans died, mostly from famine caused by German scorched-earth tactics; accelerated reforms in German colonial policy."
  ]
